opportunity cost of your time.

00:24:33.400 --> 00:24:34.870
You just spent a
year doing this.

00:24:34.870 --> 00:24:36.970
You could have been off
making a zillion dollars,

00:24:36.970 --> 00:24:39.370
like you guys all will.

00:24:39.370 --> 00:24:44.005
So we missed the opportunity
cost of your time.

00:24:44.005 --> 00:24:45.880
Let's say you could have
graduated and gotten

00:24:45.880 --> 00:24:49.200
a job at $80,000 a year.

00:24:49.200 --> 00:24:51.725
Well then, actually,
the cost of the year

00:24:51.725 --> 00:24:53.730
is not just the $40,000
you paid the programmer.

00:24:53.730 --> 00:24:57.240
It's the $80,000 that
you forgoed by working

00:24:57.240 --> 00:25:00.180
that year on your company.

00:25:00.180 --> 00:25:00.680
What else?

00:25:00.680 --> 00:25:02.780
What's the other
opportunity cost?

00:25:02.780 --> 00:25:05.450
Much smaller, but
still relevant.

00:25:05.450 --> 00:25:07.576
What could you've done
with the computer?

00:25:07.576 --> 00:25:09.340
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:25:09.340 --> 00:25:11.340
JONATHAN GRUBER: Well,
you could have done what?

00:25:11.340 --> 00:25:12.480
AUDIENCE: You
could have sold it.

00:25:12.480 --> 00:25:14.880
JONATHAN GRUBER: You could
have sold the computer, right.

00:25:14.880 --> 00:25:16.690
Now, used computers
aren't worth that much,

00:25:16.690 --> 00:25:19.470
but let's say you could
have gotten a grand for it.

00:25:19.470 --> 00:25:21.810
Well, that's an
opportunity cost.

00:25:21.810 --> 00:25:24.923
If you would just gone
on and used your--

00:25:24.923 --> 00:25:26.340
now, you might get
all the utility

00:25:26.340 --> 00:25:27.210
from the computer, whatever.

00:25:27.210 --> 00:25:28.000
Let's put that aside.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:28.890
But you just gave
it to this guy.

00:25:28.890 --> 00:25:30.810
You never touched it,
literally got rid of it.

00:25:30.810 --> 00:25:33.813
It was like you didn't have
the computer that year.

00:25:33.813 --> 00:25:34.980
Then you could have sold it.

00:25:34.980 --> 00:25:37.890
Let's say you could have
sold it for another $1,000.

00:25:37.890 --> 00:25:41.220
So now, you've paid him $40,000.

00:25:41.220 --> 00:25:44.310
You've given up $80,000
of earnings and $1,000

00:25:44.310 --> 00:25:49.590
on the computer, so your true
costs are actually $121,000.

00:25:49.590 --> 00:25:52.020
So actually, you
haven't made $20,000.

00:25:52.020 --> 00:25:55.460
You've lost $61,000.

00:25:55.460 --> 00:25:57.980
And that's why we don't care
about accounting profits.

00:25:57.980 --> 00:26:00.620
We care about economic
profits, the difference

00:26:00.620 --> 00:26:03.740
being economic profits account
for opportunity costs--

00:26:06.450 --> 00:26:07.670
very important to remember.

00:26:07.670 --> 00:26:09.080
Yeah.

00:26:09.080 --> 00:26:11.870
AUDIENCE: The profits,
