00:28:52.570 --> 00:28:53.200
This is hard.

00:28:53.200 --> 00:28:54.470
This is easy.

00:28:54.470 --> 00:28:56.750
It's price.

00:28:56.750 --> 00:28:59.000
You're given-- if
you're a price taker,

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:00.913
you're given a
price by the market.

00:29:00.913 --> 00:29:03.080
So marginal revenue for a
perfectly competitive firm

00:29:03.080 --> 00:29:05.190
is just price.

00:29:05.190 --> 00:29:14.060
So you maximize profits when
price equals marginal cost is

00:29:14.060 --> 00:29:16.300
the profit maximizing point.

00:29:16.300 --> 00:29:20.560
Profits are maximized when
price equals marginal cost.

00:29:20.560 --> 00:29:23.530
That is, you want to
produce until what

00:29:23.530 --> 00:29:26.410
you get from the next
unit equals what you

00:29:26.410 --> 00:29:29.440
spend to make the next unit.

00:29:29.440 --> 00:29:30.140
Yeah.

00:29:30.140 --> 00:29:31.530
AUDIENCE: What if you make--

00:29:31.530 --> 00:29:33.650
what if you move it
to cost a bit less

00:29:33.650 --> 00:29:36.740
and you sell it for
below the market.

00:29:36.740 --> 00:29:38.630
JONATHAN GRUBER: Let's
go to an example.

00:29:38.630 --> 00:29:42.160
So let's go to figure 7.2.

00:29:42.160 --> 00:29:46.940
Here we have the cost function
that we derived last time.

00:29:46.940 --> 00:29:50.610
C of q equals 10
plus 5q squared.

00:29:50.610 --> 00:29:54.160
You remember that
from last time.

00:29:54.160 --> 00:29:56.100
And then we have a
revenue function,

00:29:56.100 --> 00:29:59.417
and I assume the
price per unit--

00:29:59.417 --> 00:30:00.917
we have a revenue
function where I'm

00:30:00.917 --> 00:30:02.890
going to assume the
price per unit is 30.

00:30:02.890 --> 00:30:04.970
For our example, I'm going
to assume P equals 30.

00:30:08.232 --> 00:30:09.190
I've just made that up.

00:30:09.190 --> 00:30:11.960
Once again, that comes from God
in these perfectly competitive

00:30:11.960 --> 00:30:12.460
firms.

00:30:12.460 --> 00:30:14.127
They have no idea
where this comes from.

00:30:14.127 --> 00:30:15.220
It's just a price.

00:30:15.220 --> 00:30:16.300
We'll talk later
where it comes from,

00:30:16.300 --> 00:30:17.890
but for now, it's
just a given thing.

00:30:17.890 --> 00:30:19.510
Let's say it's 30.

00:30:19.510 --> 00:30:22.630
So the firm's cost
function is of the form--

00:30:22.630 --> 00:30:24.872
is graphed on the
left-hand side here.

00:30:24.872 --> 00:30:26.830
The revenue function is
simply a straight line,

00:30:26.830 --> 00:30:28.103
which is 30 times q.

00:30:28.103 --> 00:30:29.770
So if they sell one,
revenue is 30, two,

00:30:29.770 --> 00:30:31.720
revenue is 60, et cetera.

00:30:31.720 --> 00:30:35.490
And the profits are
simply the difference.

00:30:35.490 --> 00:30:41.140
So when we maximize, how
do we maximize profits?

00:30:41.140 --> 00:30:44.460
Well we want to graph--

00:30:44.460 --> 00:30:46.470
what we want to do
is graph the profit

00:30:46.470 --> 00:30:49.500
for each additional unit sold.

00:30:49.500 --> 00:30:51.960
So for example, when
you go from selling

00:30:51.960 --> 00:30:59.060
no units to selling one unit,
at no units, your cost is what?

00:30:59.060 --> 00:31:02.197
If you sell no units,
what's your cost?

00:31:02.197 --> 00:31:03.780
Somebody raise their
hand and tell me.

00:31:03.780 --> 00:31:04.335
Yeah.

00:31:04.335 --> 00:31:04.720
AUDIENCE: 10.

00:31:04.720 --> 00:31:06.370
JONATHAN GRUBER: 10,
not 0, because you

00:31:06.370 --> 00:31:07.655
have the fixed costs.

00:31:07.655 --> 00:31:08.905
Those are paid no matter what.

00:31:08.905 --> 00:31:10.110
Remember, those are
fixed in the short run.

00:31:10.110 --> 00:31:10.777
We'll come back.

00:31:10.777 --> 00:31:11.960
This is very important.

00:31:11.960 --> 00:31:15.630
So if you zero, your costs are
10, your revenues are what?

00:31:15.630 --> 00:31:18.000
0, so your profits
are negative 10.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:22.680
If you produce one
unit, what's your cost?

00:31:22.680 --> 00:31:23.360
15.

00:31:23.360 --> 00:31:24.990
What's your revenues?

00:31:24.990 --> 00:31:25.560
30.

00:31:25.560 --> 00:31:26.820
So you make a profit of 15.

00:31:29.560 --> 00:31:32.140
If you go from one unit,
now you're producing one.

00:31:32.140 --> 00:31:34.660
You want to know, should
I produce the second unit?

00:31:34.660 --> 00:31:37.090
What's the marginal
cost of the second unit?

00:31:37.090 --> 00:31:39.720
Well, we know what marginal
cost is with this function.

00:31:39.720 --> 00:31:42.460
Marginal cost, we just
differentiate this with respect

00:31:42.460 --> 00:31:46.640
to q and we get 10q
is marginal cost.

00:31:46.640 --> 00:31:49.930
So we know the marginal cost
of the second unit is what?

00:31:49.930 --> 00:31:51.632
20.

00:31:51.632 --> 00:31:53.340
What's the revenues
from the second unit?

00:31:53.340 --> 00:31:54.173
Well, that's linear.

00:31:54.173 --> 00:31:55.530
It's 30.

00:31:55.530 --> 00:32:02.120
So you're still making--
you're making a profit of 10

00:32:02.120 --> 00:32:02.720
on that unit.

00:32:02.720 --> 00:32:05.340
Now, we go to the third unit.

00:32:05.340 --> 00:32:16.613
So right, now after two units,
you are still making profit.

00:32:16.613 --> 00:32:17.780
Now we go to the third unit.

00:32:17.780 --> 00:32:19.322
It's hard, because
we're discretizing

00:32:19.322 --> 00:32:21.910
a continuous example, but
let's go to the third unit.

00:32:21.910 --> 00:32:25.080
The third unit, what's the cost?

00:32:25.080 --> 00:32:28.420
What's the marginal cost?

00:32:28.420 --> 00:32:29.470
30.

00:32:29.470 --> 00:32:31.430
What's the marginal revenue?

00:32:31.430 --> 00:32:32.260
30.

00:32:32.260 --> 00:32:36.160
So you're at the profit
maximizing point.

00:32:36.160 --> 00:32:37.450
You have climbed the hill.

00:32:37.450 --> 00:32:41.860
You have maximized your profits.

00:32:41.860 --> 00:32:44.350
What's your total
profits at that point?

00:32:44.350 --> 00:32:50.650
Well, your total profits is 3
times 30, which is 90, minus 10

00:32:50.650 --> 00:32:55.090
plus 5 times 3 squared.

00:32:55.090 --> 00:32:58.100
Minus 10 plus 45 is 55.

00:32:58.100 --> 00:33:00.780
So your total profits are 45.

00:33:00.780 --> 00:33:03.740
That's your maximum profits.

00:33:03.740 --> 00:33:05.877
That's the most
you're going to earn.

00:33:05.877 --> 00:33:08.210
Now, coming to the question
that was asked a minute ago,

00:33:08.210 --> 00:33:10.180
or a related version--

00:33:10.180 --> 00:33:13.710
wait a second, if I
sell one more unit,

00:33:13.710 --> 00:33:16.140
I still have positive profits.

00:33:16.140 --> 00:33:20.070
So my profits were 45
selling three units.

00:33:20.070 --> 00:33:24.450
The next unit, I'm
still in the black.

00:33:24.450 --> 00:33:25.260
Why not sell more?

00:33:25.260 --> 00:33:28.030
Why not sell one more unit?

00:33:28.030 --> 00:33:31.805
Why not sell that fourth unit?

00:33:31.805 --> 00:33:32.800
Yeah.

00:33:32.800 --> 00:33:33.490
AUDIENCE: Because it's
going to cost you more

00:33:33.490 --> 00:33:34.240
than it's going to give you.

00:33:34.240 --> 00:33:35.198
JONATHAN GRUBER: Right.

00:33:35.198 --> 00:33:39.030
Because we always make marginal
decisions in economics.

00:33:39.030 --> 00:33:42.250
We always ask what's the
next step I should take.

00:33:42.250 --> 00:33:44.940
And the next step
is a losing step,

00:33:44.940 --> 00:33:48.450
because the fourth unit,
what's your marginal cost?

00:33:48.450 --> 00:33:49.427
40.

00:33:49.427 --> 00:33:50.260
What's your revenue?

00:33:50.260 --> 00:33:51.330
30.

00:33:51.330 --> 00:33:54.000
So the fourth unit has
a negative 10 profit,

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:56.310
so you don't want to make it.

00:33:56.310 --> 00:34:01.860
So profit maximization is
a hill-climbing exercise.

00:34:01.860 --> 00:34:04.025
I like to think of it, and
I describe in my videos,

00:34:04.025 --> 00:34:05.400
I think of it as
it's like you're

00:34:05.400 --> 00:34:08.060
climbing a hill blindfolded.

00:34:08.060 --> 00:34:12.860
All you know is whether you're
stepping up or stepping down.

00:34:12.860 --> 00:34:16.570
And you need to figure out
when you get to the peak.

00:34:16.570 --> 00:34:18.880
If you step up, if your
next step is upward,

00:34:18.880 --> 00:34:20.568
you must be short of the peak.

00:34:20.568 --> 00:34:23.110
If your next step is downward,
you must have passed the peak.

00:34:23.110 --> 00:34:25.693
It's just keep going till your
next step leads to a flat part.

00:34:25.693 --> 00:34:28.060
Your next steps, right
in front of the other.

00:34:28.060 --> 00:34:30.190
That's what profit
maximization is.

00:34:30.190 --> 00:34:31.605
The key thing is you can--

00:34:31.605 --> 00:34:32.980
the key thing
about the blindfold

00:34:32.980 --> 00:34:34.688
is you don't need to
see the big picture.

00:34:34.688 --> 00:34:37.810
All you need to know is, is my
next step increasing my profits

00:34:37.810 --> 00:34:38.920
or decreasing my profits?

00:34:38.920 --> 00:34:40.840
If it's increasing,
I'm doing it.

00:34:40.840 --> 00:34:42.659
If it's decreasing,
I'm going backwards.

00:34:42.659 --> 00:34:45.159
That's all you need to know,
is just think about putting one

00:34:45.159 --> 00:34:46.284
foot in front of the other.

00:34:46.284 --> 00:34:49.060
Does that next unit make
me money or lose me money?

00:34:51.582 --> 00:34:53.540
So that is how we think
of profit maximization.

00:34:53.540 --> 00:34:54.040
Yeah.

00:34:54.040 --> 00:34:56.259
AUDIENCE: So what's
the next [INAUDIBLE]??

00:34:56.259 --> 00:34:57.680
You just stop it or--

00:34:57.680 --> 00:35:00.110
JONATHAN GRUBER: Well, that
is the optimal production.

00:35:00.110 --> 00:35:03.020
That's pinning down how
much you want to produce.

00:35:03.020 --> 00:35:05.150
Remember I said at
the biggest lecture,

00:35:05.150 --> 00:35:07.520
the problem with
producer theory is

00:35:07.520 --> 00:35:10.057
we have some set of
relationships between how

00:35:10.057 --> 00:35:11.140
much we produce and costs.

00:35:11.140 --> 00:35:12.260
It doesn't tell you how
much you should produce.

00:35:12.260 --> 00:35:13.940
This tells you how
much to produce.

00:35:13.940 --> 00:35:17.360
You have now solved
the firm's problem.

00:35:17.360 --> 00:35:19.880
This one extra-- this imposition
of the perfect competition

00:35:19.880 --> 00:35:25.010
constraint has allowed us to
finally solve the problem.

00:35:25.010 --> 00:35:26.630
We have now solved
it, and we've said

00:35:26.630 --> 00:35:29.150
that the firm, given
this cost function

00:35:29.150 --> 00:35:32.540
and given a price of 30, a firm
should produce three units.

00:35:32.540 --> 00:35:34.500
Done.

