00:36:31.820 --> 00:36:34.220
way harder than you think.

00:36:34.220 --> 00:36:36.260
So we're starting-- once
again, in economics,

00:36:36.260 --> 00:36:37.700
we always start with
simplifying assumptions

00:36:37.700 --> 00:36:38.720
to draw general lessons.

00:36:38.720 --> 00:36:39.680
Then we'll make some
more, and then we'll

00:36:39.680 --> 00:36:40.790
come back to the
more complicated,

00:36:40.790 --> 00:36:41.780
real-world examples.

00:36:41.780 --> 00:36:43.430
But it turns out
virtually everything

00:36:43.430 --> 00:36:46.600
we learn here is
still going to hold.

00:36:46.600 --> 00:36:47.860
Yeah.

00:36:47.860 --> 00:36:49.470
AUDIENCE: So if--

00:36:53.880 --> 00:36:55.940
JONATHAN GRUBER: We
can go back to it.

00:36:55.940 --> 00:36:59.060
So now let's ask, how
big is the firm's profit?

00:36:59.060 --> 00:37:02.090
How do we measure the
size of the profit?

00:37:02.090 --> 00:37:09.230
Profit, if we think
about profits per unit,

00:37:09.230 --> 00:37:12.680
profits equals
revenue minus costs.

00:37:12.680 --> 00:37:16.550
So profits per
unit, profits per q,

00:37:16.550 --> 00:37:20.840
equals revenues per
q minus costs per q.

00:37:20.840 --> 00:37:23.300
What is this term, cost
divided by quantity?

00:37:23.300 --> 00:37:25.390
What do we call that?

00:37:25.390 --> 00:37:26.860
Average costs.

00:37:26.860 --> 00:37:28.900
And how much do
you get per unit?

00:37:28.900 --> 00:37:30.400
You just get the price.

00:37:30.400 --> 00:37:34.180
So dR dq and R over
q are the same.

00:37:34.180 --> 00:37:35.980
In a competitive
market, marginal price

00:37:35.980 --> 00:37:37.272
and average price are the same.

00:37:37.272 --> 00:37:38.660
It's the price.

00:37:38.660 --> 00:37:40.820
So this just says
profits are equal--

00:37:40.820 --> 00:37:46.140
profits for q are equal to
price minus average cost.

00:37:46.140 --> 00:37:50.300
So your per-unit profits is
price minus average cost.

00:37:50.300 --> 00:37:58.190
And we can see
that in figure 7.3.

00:37:58.190 --> 00:38:02.760
Figure 7.3 shows our cost curves
for this 10 plus 5q squared

00:38:02.760 --> 00:38:05.290
function we derived before.

00:38:05.290 --> 00:38:07.930
And you can see we have
an average total cost

00:38:07.930 --> 00:38:10.630
curve, which first declines
and then increases.

00:38:10.630 --> 00:38:12.580
We have a marginal cost curve.

00:38:12.580 --> 00:38:16.310
And then we have an average
cost curve, average total cost

00:38:16.310 --> 00:38:16.810
curve.

00:38:16.810 --> 00:38:18.977
And then we have average
variable and average fixed.

00:38:18.977 --> 00:38:23.020
Now, we already announced
that the optimal production

00:38:23.020 --> 00:38:28.070
level was three, where
price hit marginal cost.

00:38:28.070 --> 00:38:29.540
What's our profit at three?

00:38:29.540 --> 00:38:33.080
Our profit is the difference
between that price

00:38:33.080 --> 00:38:35.360
and the average
cost of three units

00:38:35.360 --> 00:38:37.860
over all the units we produce.

00:38:37.860 --> 00:38:41.130
So the profit is actually 30.

00:38:41.130 --> 00:38:43.200
So there's a discreteness
problem here.

00:38:43.200 --> 00:38:44.430
I have to work this out.

00:38:44.430 --> 00:38:46.290
The problem, I said 45 before--

00:38:46.290 --> 00:38:47.460
it's 45 mathematically.

00:38:47.460 --> 00:38:49.212
It's 30 in this because
of the continuity

00:38:49.212 --> 00:38:50.670
problem of the sort
of discreteness

00:38:50.670 --> 00:38:51.930
between two and three.

00:38:51.930 --> 00:38:54.870
So the bottom line is,
in a continuous example,

00:38:54.870 --> 00:38:56.030
this would be the same.

00:38:56.030 --> 00:38:57.750
And the bottom
line is the profit,

00:38:57.750 --> 00:39:03.150
is the difference between the
price and the average cost

00:39:03.150 --> 00:39:06.560
times the number of units sold.

00:39:06.560 --> 00:39:10.850
That's going to be the
bottom line profit.

00:39:10.850 --> 00:39:16.455
Average cost here
is 10 over 3 is 3.

00:39:16.455 --> 00:39:18.830
Let's see, let's make sure
we've got the math right here.

00:39:18.830 --> 00:39:22.430
Average cost is 10
plus 5q squared.

00:39:22.430 --> 00:39:26.600
So average cost is
10 over q plus 5q.

00:39:26.600 --> 00:39:36.080
q is 3, so it's 3.33
plus 15, which is 18.33.

00:39:36.080 --> 00:39:37.860
Yeah, no, my math
was right with 45.

00:39:37.860 --> 00:39:41.060
This graph is wrong.

00:39:41.060 --> 00:39:44.570
So our average cost is 18.33.

00:39:44.570 --> 00:39:47.630
What's the revenue
at that point?

00:39:47.630 --> 00:39:49.490
It's 30.

00:39:49.490 --> 00:39:53.880
30 minus 18.33 times 3 is 45.

00:39:53.880 --> 00:39:56.150
So it is 45.

00:39:56.150 --> 00:39:57.140
Is that right?

00:39:57.140 --> 00:40:00.980
30 minus 18, 12 point--

00:40:00.980 --> 00:40:02.060
no, that's wrong.

00:40:02.060 --> 00:40:04.070
No, 30, no, I got that wrong.

00:40:04.070 --> 00:40:05.930
You're right.

00:40:05.930 --> 00:40:08.510
It's 35.

00:40:08.510 --> 00:40:10.220
So it all comes
from the discrete--

00:40:10.220 --> 00:40:12.860
it's all about the problem
of a very discrete function

00:40:12.860 --> 00:40:14.960
versus a continuous function.

00:40:14.960 --> 00:40:16.475
The bottom line is this--

00:40:16.475 --> 00:40:18.820
did I get right?

00:40:18.820 --> 00:40:23.120
Yeah, 11.67 times 3 is 35.

00:40:23.120 --> 00:40:28.150
So the bottom line is, we got
45 from a hill-climbing exercise

00:40:28.150 --> 00:40:30.518
and 35 from this
graph is basically

00:40:30.518 --> 00:40:32.310
a discreteness problem,
that in some sense,

00:40:32.310 --> 00:40:34.910
in this continuous function,
they give you the same thing.

00:40:34.910 --> 00:40:36.743
The bottom line is
the profit is equal

00:40:36.743 --> 00:40:39.160
to-- we'll be clear on this
in the problem sets and exams,

00:40:39.160 --> 00:40:40.360
what we're looking for.

00:40:40.360 --> 00:40:42.360
The bottom line is the
profit is the difference.

00:40:42.360 --> 00:40:44.800
The profit per unit
is the difference

00:40:44.800 --> 00:40:48.040
between the average
costs, and the price

00:40:48.040 --> 00:40:50.650
that you get for that unit.

00:40:50.650 --> 00:40:53.215
Now, with that in
mind, let me ask you

00:40:53.215 --> 00:40:55.140
the following question--

00:40:55.140 --> 00:41:01.200
what if I imposed a
tax of $1 per unit?

00:41:01.200 --> 00:41:09.550
What if I imposed a
tax of $10 per unit?

00:41:09.550 --> 00:41:12.820
What if I imposed a
tax of $10 per unit?

00:41:12.820 --> 00:41:18.730
A $10 per unit tax, what would
that do to the cost curve?

00:41:18.730 --> 00:41:20.980
Somebody, without looking
at the handout and cheating,

00:41:20.980 --> 00:41:23.980
somebody tell me what's
the new cost curve

00:41:23.980 --> 00:41:26.050
if I impose a $10 per unit tax?

00:41:29.830 --> 00:41:31.870
What's the new cost curve?

00:41:31.870 --> 00:41:33.220
What was the old cost curve?

00:41:33.220 --> 00:41:34.970
The old cost curve was
10 plus 5q squared.

00:41:34.970 --> 00:41:36.260
What's the new cost curve?

00:41:36.260 --> 00:41:38.313
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:38.313 --> 00:41:39.730
JONATHAN GRUBER:
That's the answer

00:41:39.730 --> 00:41:41.470
that almost everyone always
gives the first time,

00:41:41.470 --> 00:41:42.390
but it's not right.

00:41:42.390 --> 00:41:44.440
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:44.440 --> 00:41:47.230
JONATHAN GRUBER: 10 plus
5q squared plus 10q,

00:41:47.230 --> 00:41:49.910
because I said per
unit I charge $10.

00:41:49.910 --> 00:41:52.660
If I'd said a fixed tax of
$10, you would've been right.

00:41:52.660 --> 00:41:54.160
It would've been
20 plus 5q squared,

00:41:54.160 --> 00:41:57.490
but it's not, because it's
a per unit tax of $10.

00:41:57.490 --> 00:41:58.136
Yeah.

00:41:58.136 --> 00:42:01.527
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:42:01.527 --> 00:42:03.360
JONATHAN GRUBER: We'll
see that in a second.

00:42:03.360 --> 00:42:05.890
It's just an easy
way to explain it.

00:42:05.890 --> 00:42:06.850
So that's the new--

00:42:06.850 --> 00:42:11.500
with a tax of $10 per
unit, the new cost function

00:42:11.500 --> 00:42:15.010
is 10 plus 5q squared plus 10q.

00:42:15.010 --> 00:42:16.690
Oh, good, we didn't
show that in 7.4.

00:42:16.690 --> 00:42:18.680
So what does that do?

00:42:18.680 --> 00:42:22.140
Well, we can go to
Figure 7.4 and see that.

00:42:22.140 --> 00:42:27.330
Here, the marginal cost
and the average cost

00:42:27.330 --> 00:42:29.790
have both risen by 10.

00:42:29.790 --> 00:42:33.720
The old marginal cost was 10q.

00:42:33.720 --> 00:42:36.010
Now, it's 10q plus 10.

00:42:36.010 --> 00:42:41.050
So marginal cost
is now 10q plus 10.

00:42:41.050 --> 00:42:47.140
Average cost used to
be 10 over q plus 5q.

00:42:47.140 --> 00:42:53.180
Now it's 10 over
q plus 5q plus 10.

00:42:53.180 --> 00:42:55.370
So the bottom line is both
marginal and average cost

00:42:55.370 --> 00:42:58.307
have shifted up by 10.

00:42:58.307 --> 00:42:59.140
What does that mean?

00:42:59.140 --> 00:43:02.430
Well, first of all, it
changes optimal production.

00:43:02.430 --> 00:43:06.630
If marginal cost is 10q plus
10, and our optimization

00:43:06.630 --> 00:43:09.120
is set price equals
the marginal cost,

00:43:09.120 --> 00:43:13.800
now we're setting 30
equals 10q plus 10.

00:43:13.800 --> 00:43:18.660
30 equals 10q plus 10, which
says the optimal q drops to 2.

00:43:21.230 --> 00:43:26.030
Subtract 10 from 30, divide
by 10, you get the optimal q.

00:43:26.030 --> 00:43:31.370
Now that falls to 2, so now, you
only want to produce two units,

00:43:31.370 --> 00:43:33.920
because the marginal
cost is higher

00:43:33.920 --> 00:43:35.540
but the price is the same.

00:43:35.540 --> 00:43:37.490
You're going to produce less.

00:43:37.490 --> 00:43:39.920
So now, you're only going
to produce two units.

00:43:39.920 --> 00:43:42.080
And you could see
that in the graph,

00:43:42.080 --> 00:43:44.967
that your marginal cost hits
the price now at two units,

00:43:44.967 --> 00:43:46.550
rather than hitting
it at three units.

00:43:46.550 --> 00:43:49.100
You see that in Figure 7.4.

00:43:49.100 --> 00:43:51.080
Your average cost
is also higher,

00:43:51.080 --> 00:43:54.770
so you're going to make
less profits per unit.

00:43:54.770 --> 00:43:58.550
So you're producing
fewer units and making

00:43:58.550 --> 00:44:00.030
less profit per unit.

00:44:00.030 --> 00:44:02.780
So the entire
rectangle is shrunk.

00:44:02.780 --> 00:44:09.085
The rectangle has shrunk.

00:44:09.085 --> 00:44:10.460
Yes, the entire
rectangle shrunk.

00:44:10.460 --> 00:44:13.380
It shrunk because you're
selling fewer units.

00:44:13.380 --> 00:44:15.710
And it shrunk because
you're getting

00:44:15.710 --> 00:44:18.715
less surplus per-- you're
getting less profit per unit.

00:44:18.715 --> 00:44:23.000
Remember, profit
per unit is price

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:26.760
minus average cost over quantity
or price minus average cost.

00:44:26.760 --> 00:44:28.670
Since average cost
is higher, you're

00:44:28.670 --> 00:44:29.900
getting less profit per unit.

00:44:29.900 --> 00:44:33.570
You're selling fewer units
at less profit per unit.

00:44:33.570 --> 00:44:37.190
So that tax has significantly
lowered your profit.

00:44:37.190 --> 00:44:39.428
Questions about that?

00:44:39.428 --> 00:44:40.470
Doesn't have to be a tax.

00:44:40.470 --> 00:44:42.630
If I'd said suddenly,
whatever you're producing,

00:44:42.630 --> 00:44:45.090
there was a change in
what it costs to produce,

00:44:45.090 --> 00:44:46.710
any change in what
something costs

00:44:46.710 --> 00:44:51.450
to produce in the
production function

00:44:51.450 --> 00:44:54.040
can ultimately affect how
much you sell and you profit.

00:44:54.040 --> 00:44:56.760
So one excise you can
show yourself at home,

00:44:56.760 --> 00:45:01.622
imagine that I had said
there was a fixed tax of 10.

00:45:01.622 --> 00:45:04.080
Actually, let me ask you this
question-- imagine I had said

00:45:04.080 --> 00:45:06.862
there was a fixed tax of 10.

00:45:06.862 --> 00:45:08.570
How would that have
affected your profit?

00:45:08.570 --> 00:45:11.860
How would that affect the
amount you sell and your profit?

00:45:11.860 --> 00:45:14.312
It's a fixed tax of
10, not 10 per unit.

00:45:14.312 --> 00:45:16.270
How would that affect
how many units you'd sell

00:45:16.270 --> 00:45:17.080
and what your profit is?

00:45:17.080 --> 00:45:17.690
Yeah.

00:45:17.690 --> 00:45:19.310
AUDIENCE: Both [INAUDIBLE]
would have less profit.

00:45:19.310 --> 00:45:20.040
JONATHAN GRUBER: Exactly.

00:45:20.040 --> 00:45:21.810
You'd sell-- why would
you sell the same amount?

00:45:21.810 --> 00:45:23.030
AUDIENCE: Wouldn't
affect your MC.

00:45:23.030 --> 00:45:25.490
JONATHAN GRUBER: It wouldn't
affect your marginal cost.

00:45:25.490 --> 00:45:27.200
Remember, profit
maximization is where

00:45:27.200 --> 00:45:29.270
marginal cost equals price.

00:45:29.270 --> 00:45:31.980
If I have a fixed tax, that's
an effective marginal cost,

00:45:31.980 --> 00:45:34.147
but it does lower your
profits, because you've still

00:45:34.147 --> 00:45:35.560
got to pay that extra tax.

00:45:35.560 --> 00:45:38.080
So here, your profits
get doubly hit.

00:45:38.080 --> 00:45:40.720
You sell less, and you
make less per unit.

00:45:40.720 --> 00:45:44.392
With a flat tax, you would
sell the same amount,

00:45:44.392 --> 00:45:45.600
but you'd make less per unit.

00:45:45.600 --> 00:45:46.933
That's an important distinction.

00:45:46.933 --> 00:45:48.630
I think I'll add
that for next year.

00:45:48.630 --> 00:45:51.640
Now, one other important point--

00:45:51.640 --> 00:45:54.320
the firm has one other
decision to make here

00:45:54.320 --> 00:45:56.730
that we haven't covered
yet, which is that it has

00:45:56.730 --> 00:45:59.010
to decide whether to shut down.

00:45:59.010 --> 00:46:01.592
Now, remember I said
there's no entry and exit.

00:46:01.592 --> 00:46:04.050
That means you can't literally
leave and go somewhere else,

00:46:04.050 --> 00:46:06.307
but you can just walk away.

00:46:06.307 --> 00:46:08.640
You can just literally say,
look, I'm not in this market

00:46:08.640 --> 00:46:09.520
anymore.

00:46:09.520 --> 00:46:11.850
I'm not going to go set
up shop somewhere else,

00:46:11.850 --> 00:46:14.850
but I'm not in this
market anymore.

00:46:14.850 --> 00:46:18.757
So the question is,
when would you do so?

00:46:18.757 --> 00:46:19.840
So I'm going to get to it.

00:46:19.840 --> 00:46:20.910
Hold on.

00:46:20.910 --> 00:46:22.045
Is it a question or answer?

00:46:22.045 --> 00:46:23.670
If it's an answer,
